        text: 'These are distinct conditions that share a root word but involve different anatomy, different pathophysiology, and different treatments. Endometriosis involves tissue similar to the uterine lining growing outside the uterus, in the pelvis, on the ovaries, and in other extra-uterine locations. It drives chronic pain, adhesion formation, and in many women, infertility. Takebayashi et al. 2014 documented that the two conditions can coexist, meaning a patient can have both simultaneously. But they are evaluated differently, treated differently, and should not be conflated. If you have been told you have one and continue to have unexplained symptoms or reproductive failure, ask whether the other has been assessed. See our endometriosis guide for a full account of that condition. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.',
      },
