      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'CD138 immunohistochemistry on endometrial biopsy is the current diagnostic standard. CD138 is a marker expressed by plasma cells. Plasma cells are not normally found in the endometrial stroma. When they are identified on a biopsy specimen using CD138 staining, that is the histologic confirmation of CE. The biopsy itself is a minimally invasive office procedure. Hysteroscopy can raise clinical suspicion by revealing characteristic patterns such as focal hyperemia, micropolyps, or stromal edema, per Park et al. 2017, but hysteroscopy cannot confirm the diagnosis on its own. A normal hysteroscopy does not exclude CE. The biopsy is necessary. Microbial culture complements the histologic evaluation but also cannot replace it. If you have had hysteroscopy without a subsequent biopsy with CD138 staining, CE has not been fully evaluated. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.',
      },
