      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Why does mainstream care rarely test for chronic endometritis?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Several factors compound to create the diagnostic gap. CE produces no dramatic symptoms in most patients, so it does not generate the clinical urgency that prompts investigation. The diagnostic test requires an endometrial biopsy with specific CD138 immunohistochemistry, which is a more involved step than bloodwork or imaging. Awareness of CE\'s role in recurrent pregnancy loss and implantation failure has grown in the reproductive literature over the past decade but has not uniformly reached routine clinical practice. A 2022 survey of practicing obstetricians and gynecologists found concerning gaps in awareness of CE\'s pathophysiology, diagnostic criteria, and clinical implications, per Margulies et al. 2022. The result is that women with "unexplained" recurrent pregnancy loss or implantation failure frequently complete a standard workup that leaves CE unevaluated. The workup is not wrong. It is incomplete. CE requires asking the next question. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.',
      },
