        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Hysteroscopy is not required for the diagnosis of CE, but it is a useful complementary investigation. The diagnostic standard is endometrial biopsy with CD138 immunohistochemistry. A biopsy can be performed without hysteroscopy as a separate office procedure. Hysteroscopy adds value by visualizing the uterine cavity for characteristic CE findings (micropolyps, focal hyperemia, stromal edema) and for identifying co-occurring structural pathology such as endometrial polyps, per Vitagliano et al. 2021. In some clinical settings, hysteroscopy and biopsy are done together. In others, the biopsy is performed first and hysteroscopy is added if indicated. The key point: a hysteroscopy without a CD138 biopsy does not diagnose CE, and a normal-appearing hysteroscopy does not exclude it. The diagnosis lives in the tissue. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.',
      },
    },
