        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Partner treatment depends on which organism was identified. When Mycoplasma genitalium is found, simultaneous treatment of the male partner is clearly supported: this organism is sexually transmitted, and guidelines consistently recommend treating both partners. When Ureaplasma urealyticum or Mycoplasma hominis is cultured, the evidence for routine partner treatment is weaker, and major STI guidelines do not mandate it. Many clinicians specializing in infertility and CE do treat the male partner empirically in these cases, particularly when reproductive failure has been recurrent, but this is a clinical judgment call rather than a protocol requirement. Whether partner treatment is indicated depends on the specific organism found, the culture sensitivity results, and the judgment of the treating clinician. Beyond the CE-specific question, both partners in any couple with recurrent pregnancy loss or implantation failure should have a complete reproductive evaluation. Male factor is solely responsible in approximately 20% of couples and contributes in an additional 30 to 40%. CE in the female partner does not complete the workup. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.',
