      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'I had a CD138 biopsy that was negative. Could I still have chronic endometritis?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'A negative CD138 biopsy substantially reduces the probability of CE, but a few caveats apply. First, the threshold for "positive" is not standardized across laboratories: some use one plasma cell per high-power field, others require five or more. The laboratory\'s specific protocol matters. Second, CE can be patchy, meaning that a biopsy from one area of the endometrium might not sample the affected region. Third, the timing of the biopsy within the cycle can affect results: most protocols recommend sampling in the proliferative phase, and sampling during the secretory phase may reduce sensitivity. If your biopsy was done by a center that did not use CD138 IHC specifically, but relied on standard hematoxylin and eosin staining alone, the sensitivity is lower. If your clinical picture strongly suggests CE and a single biopsy was negative, a repeat biopsy at a center experienced in CE diagnosis is a reasonable next step. A negative biopsy done correctly by an experienced laboratory carries more weight than one where the protocol is uncertain. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.',
