              <li><strong>In a cohort of 360 women with recurrent pregnancy loss, 56.7% had CE identified on hysteroscopy.</strong> After antibiotic treatment, the subsequent live birth rate in those treated was significantly higher than before treatment. This is a diagnosable, treatable condition, per <a href="/library/chronic-endometritis-due-to-common-bacteria-is-prevalent-in-women-with-recurrent-recyfpe9a4szxychl/">Cicinelli et al. 2013</a>.</li>
              <li><strong>Untreated CE significantly reduces pregnancy rates and live birth rates.</strong> In a systematic review and meta-analysis of 4,145 patients, women with CE had lower ongoing pregnancy and live birth rates compared to unaffected women. CE resolution after antibiotic therapy substantially improved those outcomes, per <a href="/library/chronic-endometritis-in-infertile-women-impact-of-untreated-disease-plasma-cell--recnapfelxmnub1sq/">Vitagliano et al. 2022</a>.</li>
              <li><strong>Antibiotic treatment of CE improves reproductive outcomes in RPL and implantation failure populations.</strong> In specialist centers that perform post-treatment retest biopsy, the outcome data are compelling: McQueen 2014 reported a cumulative live birth rate of 88% among 35 treated women across the post-treatment follow-up window, compared to a per-pregnancy live birth rate of 7% in those same patients before treatment, rising to 56% after treatment, per <a href="/library/chronic-endometritis-in-women-with-recurrent-early-pregnancy-loss-andor-fetal-de-EAqhlgQh/">McQueen et al. 2014</a>.</li>
