          </section>

          <section id="outcomes">
            <h2>Outcomes After Treatment</h2>

            <p>The outcome data for CE treatment are encouraging. They are also heterogeneous, and that honesty belongs in this section.</p>

            <p>The most consistent finding across studies is directional: treating CE improves reproductive outcomes compared to not treating it. The McQueen et al. cohort showed a cumulative live birth rate of 88% in treated patients, compared to a per-pregnancy live birth rate of 7% before treatment in those same patients. The Cicinelli et al. 2013 cohort showed significantly higher subsequent pregnancy success rates in women whose CE resolved versus those in whom it did not. The Vitagliano et al. 2022 meta-analysis showed that CE cure normalized outcomes to levels comparable to unaffected patients.</p>

            <p>The heterogeneity in the literature is real and worth naming. Prevalence estimates vary widely because studies use different diagnostic thresholds for plasma cell counts on IHC, different histologic protocols, and different patient populations. Some studies use hysteroscopy as the primary diagnostic modality; others use histology; others use both. The threshold at which CE is called "positive" is not standardized across centers. This means the absolute prevalence numbers cited in different papers are not always directly comparable.</p>

            <p>Similarly, treatment protocols vary. Doxycycline regimens differ in duration. Some centers add a second antibiotic. Some culture-guide therapy; others treat empirically. This variation means that "CE treatment" in one study is not identical to "CE treatment" in another.</p>

            <p>What the evidence does support, consistently: the presence of CE is a negative predictor of reproductive success, its absence is not, and treatment-induced resolution is associated with improved outcomes. For a patient with recurrent loss or implantation failure and an untested endometrium, that is clinically meaningful. It means there is a diagnosable, treatable possibility that has not been excluded.</p>
          </section>

          <section id="when-to-suspect">
            <h2>When to Suspect Chronic Endometritis</h2>

            <p>CE has no pathognomonic symptom. Its subclinical character is part of its clinical danger. But there are patterns worth recognizing.</p>

            <p><strong>History patterns that should prompt CE evaluation:</strong></p>

            <p>Repeated implantation failure after embryo transfer, particularly when embryo quality has been assessed as adequate and no structural uterine abnormality has been found. Two or more failed transfers in this context raises the pre-test probability of CE substantially.</p>

            <p>Recurrent pregnancy loss without an identified cause. If the standard RPL workup (karyotype, thrombophilia, uterine anatomy, thyroid) has been completed and returned non-explanatory results, CE is an active diagnostic possibility that deserves investigation. The question is simple: has an endometrial biopsy with CD138 IHC been done? If not, it has not been excluded.</p>

            <p>Persistent brown spotting at the end of cycles or into the early cycle days. This is not specific to CE, but it is a charted observation that accumulates clinical value when combined with a history of reproductive failure. It reflects atypical endometrial shedding and can be a downstream expression of the inflammatory state.</p>

            <p>Unusual or prolonged menstrual bleeding with no structural cause identified on imaging. Again, not specific, but noteworthy in context.</p>

            <p>Post-procedural history. Women who have had dilation and curettage (D&amp;C) for miscarriage management, uterine instrumentation for polyp removal, or retained products of conception have had entry points for bacterial colonization. CE has been documented following these procedures.</p>

            <p>Any patient told she has no fixable cause for repeated pregnancy loss or implantation failure should ask, explicitly: has CE been evaluated with an endometrial biopsy and CD138 staining? If the answer is no, that answer matters.</p>
          </section>

          <section id="acute-ce">
            <h2>Acute Endometritis: A Brief Note</h2>

            <p>This guide is about chronic endometritis. Acute endometritis is a different clinical entity.</p>

            <p>Acute endometritis is a symptomatic infection of the uterine lining, typically occurring after childbirth (postpartum endometritis), after pregnancy loss managed by D&amp;C, or following uterine instrumentation. It presents with fever, uterine tenderness, and abnormal discharge. It is caused by ascending polymicrobial infection, is treated with systemic antibiotics, and is generally diagnosed and managed within the acute care setting.</p>

            <p>Acute endometritis is mainstream territory. It is recognized, it is symptomatic, and it is treated. The diagnostic and management gaps that define CE do not apply to acute endometritis in the same way.</p>

            <p>A woman who had acute endometritis after a delivery or procedure may subsequently develop CE as a sequela, but the two diagnoses are distinct and occur on different timescales. If you are experiencing fever, pelvic pain, and abnormal discharge in the postpartum period or after a procedure, seek evaluation through your obstetric or gynecologic provider. That is not what this page is about.</p>
          </section>

          <section id="preparing-for-a-consult">
            <h2>Preparing for a Consult</h2>

            <p>If you have had recurrent pregnancy loss or repeated implantation failure and CE has not been evaluated, here is what to bring to the conversation.</p>

            <p><strong>Operative and procedure reports.</strong> If you have had hysteroscopy, D&amp;C, or any uterine procedure, request the full operative report, not just a summary. The report tells a clinician what was seen, how the uterine cavity looked, and whether any biopsy was taken. If a biopsy was taken, request the pathology report: it should specify whether CD138 IHC was included and whether plasma cells were identified.</p>

            <p><strong>IVF records.</strong> If you have had IVF cycles, the embryo transfer records describe embryo quality at the time of transfer. If transfers repeatedly failed with good-quality embryos and no endometrial biopsy was done before or between cycles, that is the gap to name explicitly.</p>

            <p><strong>Cycle charts.</strong> Charted cycles create a documented record of spotting patterns, bleeding character, cycle length variation, and any atypical symptom timing. If you have been charting, bring that record. If you have not been charting, starting now will give a clinician observable data.</p>

            <p><strong>The question to ask directly:</strong> Has CE been evaluated with an endometrial biopsy and CD138 immunohistochemistry? Not: has my uterus been looked at. Not: was my bloodwork normal. Specifically: has the endometrium been biopsied and the specimen stained for CD138?</p>

            <p>If the answer is no, that is the starting point.</p>
          </section>

          <section id="faq">
            <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

            <div class="faq-accordion" data-pagefind-ignore>
              <details>
                <summary>Is endometritis the same as endometriosis?</summary>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                  <p>These are distinct conditions that share a root word but involve different anatomy, different pathophysiology, and different treatments. Endometriosis involves tissue similar to the uterine lining growing outside the uterus, in the pelvis, on the ovaries, and in other extra-uterine locations. It drives chronic pain, adhesion formation, and in many women, infertility. <a href="/library/the-association-between-endometriosis-and-chronic-endometritis-recid8hvquzgigrgk/">Takebayashi et al. 2014</a> documented that the two conditions can coexist, meaning a patient can have both simultaneously. But they are evaluated differently, treated differently, and should not be conflated. If you have been told you have one and continue to have unexplained symptoms or reproductive failure, ask whether the other has been assessed. See our <a href="/endometriosis/">endometriosis guide</a> for a full account of that condition. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.</p>
                </div>
              </details>

              <details>
                <summary>How is chronic endometritis diagnosed?</summary>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                  <p>CD138 immunohistochemistry on endometrial biopsy is the current diagnostic standard. CD138 is a marker expressed by plasma cells. Plasma cells are not normally found in the endometrial stroma. When they are identified on a biopsy specimen using CD138 staining, that is the histologic confirmation of CE. The biopsy itself is a minimally invasive office procedure. Hysteroscopy can raise clinical suspicion by revealing characteristic patterns such as focal hyperemia, micropolyps, or stromal edema, per <a href="/library/chronic-endometritis-and-infertility-rechb8anslz91hhrb/">Park et al. 2017</a>, but hysteroscopy cannot confirm the diagnosis on its own. A normal hysteroscopy does not exclude CE. The biopsy is necessary. Microbial culture complements the histologic evaluation but also cannot replace it. If you have had hysteroscopy without a subsequent biopsy with CD138 staining, CE has not been fully evaluated. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.</p>
                </div>
              </details>

              <details>
                <summary>What causes chronic endometritis?</summary>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                  <p>CE is caused by persistent abnormal bacterial colonization of the endometrium. The most commonly identified organisms are Enterobacteriaceae, Enterococcus, Streptococcus, Staphylococcus, Mycoplasma, and Ureaplasma, per <a href="/library/the-diagnosis-of-chronic-endometritis-in-infertile-asymptomatic-women-a-comparat-rec1qah2jxcen5ftk/">Moreno et al. 2018</a>. These are not organisms associated with dramatic acute illness in most patients. They produce a subclinical, chronic inflammatory state rather than the fever and pelvic pain associated with acute pelvic infection. Prior uterine instrumentation (D&amp;C, polyp removal, IVF transfers, hysteroscopy) creates potential entry points for ascending bacterial colonization. Some cases arise without a clear procedural history. The bacterial colonization triggers an abnormal immune response in the endometrium, producing the plasma cell infiltration that defines CE histologically. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.</p>
                </div>
              </details>

              <details>
                <summary>I have had repeated IVF failures. Could chronic endometritis be the reason?</summary>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                  <p>In many cases, CE is a contributing factor in repeated implantation failure that has not been found because the biopsy was not done. The evidence is substantial: CE is found in approximately 30% of women with repeated unexplained implantation failure, per <a href="/library/prevalence-of-chronic-endometritis-in-repeated-unexplained-implantation-failure--zBgeyQAb/">Cicinelli et al. 2015</a>. A 2022 systematic review and meta-analysis of 4,145 patients found that women with CE had significantly lower live birth and ongoing pregnancy rates, and that CE resolution after antibiotic treatment normalized those outcomes to levels comparable to unaffected women, per <a href="/library/chronic-endometritis-in-infertile-women-impact-of-untreated-disease-plasma-cell--recnapfelxmnub1sq/">Vitagliano et al. 2022</a>. A morphologically normal embryo placed into an inflamed endometrium cannot implant the way it should. The endometrial environment matters independent of embryo quality. If you have had transfers fail with good-quality embryos and no endometrial biopsy has been done, CE has not been excluded. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.</p>
                </div>
              </details>

              <details>
                <summary>Can chronic endometritis cause recurrent miscarriage?</summary>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                  <p>The evidence links CE to recurrent pregnancy loss across several study populations. Cicinelli et al. evaluated 360 women with unexplained recurrent miscarriage and found CE in 56.7% by hysteroscopy, confirmed by histology in 91.3% of those. After antibiotic treatment, subsequent pregnancy outcomes improved significantly in those whose CE resolved, per <a href="/library/chronic-endometritis-due-to-common-bacteria-is-prevalent-in-women-with-recurrent-recyfpe9a4szxychl/">Cicinelli et al. 2013</a>. McQueen et al. evaluated 395 women in a recurrent pregnancy loss program and found a 9% overall CE prevalence, with a subsequent cumulative live birth rate of 88% in treated patients, per <a href="/library/chronic-endometritis-in-women-with-recurrent-early-pregnancy-loss-andor-fetal-de-EAqhlgQh/">McQueen et al. 2014</a>. The mechanism is plausible: persistent endometrial inflammation impairs the implantation process and disrupts early pregnancy maintenance. For any patient told her losses are unexplained, CE evaluation with endometrial biopsy is a reasonable and low-risk investigative step that the standard RPL workup often omits. See our <a href="/miscarriage/">miscarriage and recurrent pregnancy loss guide</a> for the full RPL workup. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.</p>
                </div>
              </details>

              <details>
                <summary>Is endometritis treatable?</summary>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                  <p>Chronic endometritis is treatable with antibiotic therapy, and treatment is associated with improved reproductive outcomes in cohorts where CE was the identified factor. The standard approach is antibiotic treatment followed, in specialist centers, by a retest biopsy to confirm resolution. Doxycycline is among the most studied regimens in the literature, but specific antibiotic choice, duration, and whether combination therapy is indicated depend on the individual patient's culture results and clinical context. These are prescribing decisions for the treating clinician. In the McQueen et al. cohort, the cure rate after antibiotic treatment was 100%, with a post-treatment cumulative live birth rate of 88% in those treated, per <a href="/library/chronic-endometritis-in-women-with-recurrent-early-pregnancy-loss-andor-fetal-de-EAqhlgQh/">McQueen et al. 2014</a>. CE that does not resolve after one course of antibiotics may require a second course or a culture-guided change in regimen. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.</p>
                </div>
              </details>

              <details>
                <summary>Why does mainstream care rarely test for chronic endometritis?</summary>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                  <p>Several factors compound to create the diagnostic gap. CE produces no dramatic symptoms in most patients, so it does not generate the clinical urgency that prompts investigation. The diagnostic test requires an endometrial biopsy with specific CD138 immunohistochemistry, which is a more involved step than bloodwork or imaging. Awareness of CE's role in recurrent pregnancy loss and implantation failure has grown in the reproductive literature over the past decade but has not uniformly reached routine clinical practice. A 2022 survey of practicing obstetricians and gynecologists found concerning gaps in awareness of CE's pathophysiology, diagnostic criteria, and clinical implications, per <a href="/library/chronic-endometritis-a-prevalent-yet-poorly-understood-entity-dEI8BPHx/">Margulies et al. 2022</a>. The result is that women with "unexplained" recurrent pregnancy loss or implantation failure frequently complete a standard workup that leaves CE unevaluated. The workup is not wrong. It is incomplete. CE requires asking the next question. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.</p>
                </div>
              </details>

              <details>
                <summary>Do I need a hysteroscopy to diagnose chronic endometritis?</summary>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                  <p>Hysteroscopy is not required for the diagnosis of CE, but it is a useful complementary investigation. The diagnostic standard is endometrial biopsy with CD138 immunohistochemistry. A biopsy can be performed without hysteroscopy as a separate office procedure. Hysteroscopy adds value by visualizing the uterine cavity for characteristic CE findings (micropolyps, focal hyperemia, stromal edema) and for identifying co-occurring structural pathology such as endometrial polyps, per <a href="/library/association-between-endometrial-polyps-and-chronic-endometritis-is-it-time-for-a-recnttsdmqyb3t0iv/">Vitagliano et al. 2021</a>. In some clinical settings, hysteroscopy and biopsy are done together. In others, the biopsy is performed first and hysteroscopy is added if indicated. The key point: a hysteroscopy without a CD138 biopsy does not diagnose CE, and a normal-appearing hysteroscopy does not exclude it. The diagnosis lives in the tissue. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.</p>
                </div>
              </details>

              <details>
                <summary>Should my partner be treated too?</summary>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                  <p>Partner treatment depends on which organism was identified. When Mycoplasma genitalium is found, simultaneous treatment of the male partner is clearly supported: this organism is sexually transmitted, and guidelines consistently recommend treating both partners. When Ureaplasma urealyticum or Mycoplasma hominis is cultured, the evidence for routine partner treatment is weaker, and major STI guidelines do not mandate it. Many clinicians specializing in infertility and CE do treat the male partner empirically in these cases, particularly when reproductive failure has been recurrent, but this is a clinical judgment call rather than a protocol requirement. Whether partner treatment is indicated depends on the specific organism found, the culture sensitivity results, and the judgment of the treating clinician. Beyond the CE-specific question, both partners in any couple with recurrent pregnancy loss or implantation failure should have a complete reproductive evaluation. Male factor is solely responsible in approximately 20% of couples and contributes in an additional 30 to 40%. CE in the female partner does not complete the workup. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.</p>
                </div>
              </details>

              <details>
                <summary>I had a CD138 biopsy that was negative. Could I still have chronic endometritis?</summary>
                <div class="faq-answer">
                  <p>A negative CD138 biopsy substantially reduces the probability of CE, but a few caveats apply. First, the threshold for "positive" is not standardized across laboratories: some use one plasma cell per high-power field, others require five or more. The laboratory's specific protocol matters. Second, CE can be patchy, meaning that a biopsy from one area of the endometrium might not sample the affected region. Third, the timing of the biopsy within the cycle can affect results: most protocols recommend sampling in the proliferative phase, and sampling during the secretory phase may reduce sensitivity. If your biopsy was done by a center that did not use CD138 IHC specifically, but relied on standard hematoxylin and eosin staining alone, the sensitivity is lower. If your clinical picture strongly suggests CE and a single biopsy was negative, a repeat biopsy at a center experienced in CE diagnosis is a reasonable next step. A negative biopsy done correctly by an experienced laboratory carries more weight than one where the protocol is uncertain. Consult an RRM clinician or healthcare provider for guidance specific to your situation.</p>
                </div>
              </details>
            </div>
          </section>

